00:05:49,070 --> 00:05:52,714
wants you to remember: $10 billion. In 2024,

94
00:05:53,068 --> 00:05:56,760
Spotify announced it had paid $10 billion to the music

95
00:05:57,260 --> 00:06:01,074
industry in a single year. Cumulative total since launch: nearly

96
00:06:01,106 --> 00:06:04,631
$50 billion. They put it in a press release. They put

97
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:08,540
it in their investor call. They put a giant infographic on their blog.

98
00:06:08,733 --> 00:06:12,097
Spotify has now paid the music industry nearly $50

99
00:06:12,226 --> 00:06:15,046
billion. That sounds incredible, right?

100
00:06:15,430 --> 00:06:19,484
Wrong. Let me tell you what that number actually means, because Spotify

101
00:06:19,532 --> 00:06:23,234
is very deliberately not telling you. Paid to the

102
00:06:23,734 --> 00:06:27,436
music industry does not mean paid to artists. The music industry is a chain.

103
00:06:28,046 --> 00:06:31,051
Spotify pays the money to a distributor, DistroKid,

104
00:06:31,308 --> 00:06:34,553
TuneCore, CD Baby, or directly to a major label.

105
00:06:34,842 --> 00:06:38,361
The distributor or label takes their cut, usually 20-30%.

106
00:06:39,341 --> 00:06:42,651
Then the label takes another cut, if there's a label involved,

107
00:06:42,812 --> 00:06:45,880
usually 50-85% of what's left.

108
00:06:46,169 --> 00:06:49,785
Then the publisher takes a cut. Then the songwriter gets a sliver.

109
00:06:50,122 --> 00:06:53,704
Then, finally, the artist gets paid. If there's anything left.

110
00:06:54,202 --> 00:06:57,800
Which there usually isn't. That $10 billion headline?

111
00:06:58,218 --> 00:07:02,024
It's the top-line number, before every middleman in the chain takes

112
00:07:02,524 --> 00:07:05,879
a bite. The amount that actually hits an artist's bank account is

113
00:07:06,379 --> 00:07:09,814
a fraction of a fraction of a fraction. Now let's talk per

114
00:07:10,314 --> 00:07:13,732
stream. The widely cited industry estimate for Spotify's

115
00:07:14,232 --> 00:07:17,956
per-stream payout is between 3/10 of a cent and 5/10

116
00:07:18,133 --> 00:07:21,355
of a cent. 3 tenths of a cent to one half of a cent per

117
00:07:21,855 --> 00:07:25,810
stream. To make minimum wage in the United States, $15 an

118
00:07:25,986 --> 00:07:29,527
hour, which is itself a low bar, an artist would need roughly

119
00:07:30,027 --> 00:07:33,982
4,000 streams per hour. To make the average American salary

120
00:07:34,174 --> 00:07:38,196
of about $59,000, an artist would need around 20

121
00:07:38,696 --> 00:07:42,346
million streams in a year. 20 million. For context,

122
00:07:42,410 --> 00:07:45,711
the average song on Spotify gets about 30 streams per

123
00:07:46,211 --> 00:07:49,814
month. Not 30,000. 30. If you're a normal

124
00:07:49,974 --> 00:07:53,516
independent artist with a small but loyal audience,

125
00:07:53,805 --> 00:07:57,732
say 2,000 monthly listeners, which is actually pretty good for

126
00:07:58,232 --> 00:08:01,931
an indie, you are generating something like 60,000 streams a

127
00:08:01,963 --> 00:08:05,473
month. At 3/10 of a cent per stream, that's $180

128
00:08:06,307 --> 00:08:09,737
a month. Before distributor fees. Before label cuts.

129
00:08:10,154 --> 00:08:13,488
Before taxes. $180 for

130
00:08:13,520 --> 00:08:17,034
a month of work that probably took a year to make. And it

131
00:08:17,534 --> 00:08:21,175
gets worse. Because Spotify doesn't pay a flat rate per stream.

132
00:08:21,625 --> 00:08:25,141
The payout is determined by something called the revenue share model.

133
00:08:25,959 --> 00:08:28,736
Here's how it actually works. Every month,

134
00:08:29,106 --> 00:08:32,653
Spotify pools all of its subscription revenue from every country.

135
00:08:33,023 --> 00:08:35,992
They take their cut, roughly 30%, off the top.

136
00:08:36,474 --> 00:08:40,214
Then they divide what's left by the total number of streams across

137
00:08:40,327 --> 00:08:43,570
the entire platform, weighted by where those streams came

138
00:08:43,682 --> 00:08:47,166
from. A stream from a US subscriber is worth

139
00:08:47,230 --> 00:08:50,425
more than a stream from a Brazilian subscriber because the

140
00:08:50,506 --> 00:08:53,668
US subscriber pays more. So your payout per

141
00:08:54,168 --> 00:08:57,762
stream isn't 3 tenths of a cent. It's 3 tenths of a cent if your

142
00:08:57,811 --> 00:09:00,957
listeners are in the US. It's 1 tenth of a cent

143
00:09:01,054 --> 00:09:04,891
if they're in India. It's 7 hundredths of a cent if they're in Nigeria.

144
00:09:05,356 --> 00:09:08,871
It's 5 tenths of a cent if they're in Norway. The same song,

145
00:09:09,063 --> 00:09:12,284
the same stream, the same artist, the same 3

146
00:09:12,784 --> 00:09:16,882
minutes and 47 seconds of music worth different amounts of money depending

147
00:09:17,058 --> 00:09:20,872
on which country the listener happens to be in when they hit play.

148
00:09:21,881 --> 00:09:25,134
That's why the per-stream number you see quoted is an average.

149
00:09:25,630 --> 00:09:29,027
A meaningless average. Some artists make half a cent per

150
00:09:29,527 --> 00:09:33,065
stream, some make a tenth of a cent. Spotify knows

151
00:09:33,113 --> 00:09:36,301
this, they've known it for years. They've done nothing to fix it,

152
00:09:36,462 --> 00:09:40,034
Because the ambiguity benefits them. If nobody knows exactly

153
00:09:40,066 --> 00:09:43,558
what a stream is worth, nobody can prove they're being underpaid.

154
00:09:43,895 --> 00:09:48,204
And they are being underpaid. By every possible measure. In 2014,

155
00:09:48,653 --> 00:09:51,921
the per-stream payout was around 7 tenths of a cent.

156
00:09:52,305 --> 00:09:56,038
Today, it's 3 tenths of a cent. In a decade, the value

157
00:09:56,086 --> 00:09:59,547
of a single stream has dropped by more than half. And in that

158
00:10:00,047 --> 00:10:03,904
same decade, Spotify's revenue has more than tripled. From $5

159
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,893
billion in 2019 to over $15 billion in 2024.

160
00:10:08,422 --> 00:10:12,083
The pie got 3 times bigger. The slice that goes to artists

161
00:10:12,195 --> 00:10:15,214
got twice as small. That's not a market correction.

162
00:10:15,487 --> 00:10:19,180
That's a structural feature. Spotify has engineered their payout

163
00:10:19,680 --> 00:10:23,997
system so that as the company grows, artists get less. On purpose.

164
00:10:24,238 --> 00:10:27,947
You'd think a company that just announced record profits would share the love.

165
00:10:28,637 --> 00:10:31,849
Right? Wrong. They announced a new rule instead. And it

166
00:10:32,349 --> 00:10:36,007
might be the worst one yet. Every dollar you pay Spotify gets

167
00:10:36,104 --> 00:10:39,732
split. Here's the rough breakdown: roughly 30 cents

168
00:10:40,232 --> 00:10:44,228
goes to Spotify. That's their revenue. Their cut. Their fee for running the

169
00:10:44,728 --> 00:10:47,969
platform. Out of that 30 cents, Spotify pays for servers,

170
00:10:48,466 --> 00:10:50,698
bandwidth, app development, marketing,

171
00:10:51,131 --> 00:10:54,953
podcasts, which we'll get to, and increasingly, AI features

172
00:10:54,969 --> 00:10:58,405
that nobody asked for. The other 70 cents goes to rights holders.

173
00:10:58,758 --> 00:11:01,937
Labels, distributors, publishers, and eventually,

174
00:11:02,194 --> 00:11:05,759
maybe, artists. But that 70 cents doesn't get

175
00:11:06,259 --> 00:11:10,834
split equally. It gets split based on market share. Which means Universal

176
00:11:10,882 --> 00:11:14,897
Music Group, the largest label in the world, gets a much bigger chunk

177
00:11:14,978 --> 00:11:18,061
than an independent artist on DistroKid. Even if

178
00:11:18,093 --> 00:11:21,450
the independent artist generates the same number of streams

179
00:11:21,803 --> 00:11:25,818
as a Universal artist, the Universal artist gets paid more per

180
00:11:26,318 --> 00:11:29,800
stream. Because Universal has negotiated a better deal. This is

181
00:11:29,832 --> 00:11:33,904
the part nobody explains to you when you sign up to put your music on

182
00:11:34,404 --> 00:11:37,896
Spotify. The major labels get minimum revenue guarantees.

183
00:11:38,313 --> 00:11:42,785
They get advances. They get marketing credits. They get preferential playlist

184
00:11:42,817 --> 00:11:46,103
placement. The independent artist gets the standard rate,

185
00:11:46,360 --> 00:11:50,111
minus distribu— distributor fees, minus whatever the distributor's

186
00:11:50,611 --> 00:11:53,926
payment processor charges, minus whatever the bank charges

187
00:11:54,199 --> 00:11:58,820
to convert the currency. A major label artist might see something like 5/10

188
00:11:59,173 --> 00:12:03,588
of a cent per stream after everyone takes their cut. An independent

189
00:12:03,652 --> 00:12:07,730
artist might see 1/10 of a cent. Same platform, same listener,

190
00:12:07,762 --> 00:12:11,502
same 3-minute song. 5 times difference in payout.

191
00:12:11,695 --> 00:12:14,633
Because the system isn't designed to reward streams.

192
00:12:14,986 --> 00:12:18,100
It's designed to reward scale. And there's another wrinkle.

193
00:12:18,373 --> 00:12:21,584
Spotify has been pushing what they call Discovery Mode.

194
00:12:21,728 --> 00:12:24,857
Here's the pitch. As an artist, you can opt into

195
00:12:24,873 --> 00:12:28,594
Discovery Mode on a track, and Spotify will algorithmically boost

196
00:12:28,626 --> 00:12:31,722
that track in playlists and radio stations. More reach,

197
00:12:31,979 --> 00:12:35,171
more streams, more listeners. Sounds great. The catch?

198
00:12:35,941 --> 00:12:40,416
If you opt in, you agree to accept a lower royalty rate on streams

199
00:12:40,916 --> 00:12:44,057
of that track. Spotify doesn't tell you exactly how much lower.

200
00:12:44,426 --> 00:12:46,992
They just say it's a promotional royalty rate.

201
00:12:47,778 --> 00:12:52,014
Translation: you pay Spotify to promote your song, by accepting less money

202
00:12:52,046 --> 00:12:54,744
per stream. This is, by any reasonable definition,

203
00:12:54,936 --> 00:12:58,211
payola. Payola, the practice of paying a

204
00:12:58,711 --> 00:13:03,044
radio station to play your song, was made illegal in the United States in 1960.

205
00:13:03,670 --> 00:13:07,893
After a massive congressional investigation. Spotify reinvented

206
00:13:07,941 --> 00:13:11,328
payola, made it algorithmic, called it Discovery Mode.

207
00:13:11,553 --> 00:13:15,872
And nobody sued them. Because the legal definition of payola involves

208
00:13:15,904 --> 00:13:19,256
a direct payment. Discovery Mode isn't a direct payment.

209
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:23,471
It's a discounted royalty. Loophole closed. Loophole immediately

210
00:13:23,503 --> 00:13:26,677
reopened. Major labels use Discovery Mode freely.

211
00:13:27,030 --> 00:13:29,354
They have the volume to absorb the lower rate.

212
00:13:30,220 --> 00:13:33,842
Independent artists who use it end up paying Spotify to promote

213
00:13:34,342 --> 00:13:37,753
their own music, and the royalty hit can wipe out most of what they

214
00:13:37,849 --> 00:13:42,530
earn from the boosted streams. So, the system looks like this: Spotify

215
00:13:42,658 --> 00:13:46,650
takes 30% off the top. Then the major labels negotiate better

216
00:13:47,150 --> 00:13:51,379
rates. Then the major labels use Discovery Mode to boost their artists

217
00:13:51,395 --> 00:13:55,130
into your Discover Weekly and Release Radar playlists. Then those

218
00:13:55,226 --> 00:13:58,897
artists get more streams, which gives the major labels

219
00:13:58,945 --> 00:14:02,296
more market share. Which gives them an even bigger chunk of the

220
00:14:02,796 --> 00:14:05,774
next month's pool. The flywheel spins in one direction.

221
00:14:06,287 --> 00:14:09,974
Toward Universal, Sony, and Warner. Always, and every

222
00:14:09,990 --> 00:14:12,811
quarter, Spotify announces record revenue.

223
00:14:13,580 --> 00:14:17,041
And every quarter independent artists make less per stream than

224
00:14:17,541 --> 00:14:21,208
the quarter before. And every quarter somebody at Spotify writes a

225
00:14:21,708 --> 00:14:24,477
blog post about how the company is democratizing music.

226
00:14:25,054 --> 00:14:28,547
Democratizing. That word. I don't think it means

227
00:14:28,643 --> 00:14:32,425
what they think it means. Now, let's talk about the artists who actually

228
00:14:32,489 --> 00:14:35,790
quit. Because some of them have, and the ones who haven't are

229
00:14:36,290 --> 00:14:40,204
about to. In November 2023, Spotify quietly

230
00:14:40,704 --> 00:14:44,700
announced a change to their royalty system. Quietly is the operative word.

231
00:14:44,957 --> 00:14:47,799
It wasn't a press release. It wasn't an email to artists.

232
00:14:48,136 --> 00:14:52,006
It was a blog post on a Spotify for Artists subdomain, written in

233
00:14:52,506 --> 00:14:56,357
the driest corporate language possible, dropped on a Friday afternoon. Which,

234
00:14:56,807 --> 00:15:00,114
as anyone in PR knows, is the day you announce things you

235
00:15:00,178 --> 00:15:03,936
want people to ignore. Here's the rule: Starting in early

236
00:15:03,952 --> 00:15:07,838
2024, any track that doesn't reach 1,000 streams

237
00:15:07,902 --> 00:15:11,579
in a 12-month period earns zero royalties. Zero.

238
00:15:11,739 --> 00:15:15,416
Not less. Spotify framed this as a fight against fraud. They said

239
00:15:15,448 --> 00:15:19,174
there were tens of millions of tracks on the platform generating

240
00:15:19,318 --> 00:15:22,963
tiny amounts of money— fractions of a cent— and that those

241
00:15:23,059 --> 00:15:26,576
tracks were clogging up the system. By zeroing them

242
00:15:26,608 --> 00:15:30,285
out, they said, they could redirect that money to working artists.

243
00:15:30,798 --> 00:15:33,956
Sounds reasonable, right? Wrong.

244
00:15:34,389 --> 00:15:38,252
Here's what they didn't tell you. Roughly 2/3 of the tracks on Spotify,

245
00:15:38,653 --> 00:15:41,490
somewhere around 65 to 70 million songs,

246
00:15:41,923 --> 00:15:45,834
get fewer than 1,000 streams per year. That's not a fringe

247
00:15:45,851 --> 00:15:49,313
group of noise tracks. That's the majority of the catalog.

248
00:15:49,618 --> 00:15:53,032
Independent artists, local bands, composers,

249
00:15:53,305 --> 00:15:57,248
producers, bedroom musicians. The people Spotify claims

250
00:15:57,748 --> 00:16:01,544
to champion. Under the old system, those tracks collectively generated something

251
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:04,787
like $40 million $40 million a year. Not a lot per artist,

252
00:16:05,092 --> 00:16:09,477
but it was real money. A few hundred bucks for an indie musician is groceries.

253
00:16:09,750 --> 00:16:12,978
It's a guitar string change. It's gas to drive to the next

254
00:16:13,026 --> 00:16:16,865
gig. Spotify took that $40 million and redistributed it.

255
00:16:17,219 --> 00:16:20,559
Not to working artists. To the major labels.

256
00:16:20,832 --> 00:16:24,655
Here's how the redistribution actually works. The money saved

257
00:16:24,671 --> 00:16:27,835
from the demonetized tracks goes back into the revenue share

258
00:16:27,980 --> 00:16:31,576
pool. That pool is then divided based on total market

259
00:16:32,076 --> 00:16:34,915
share. And who has the biggest market share on Spotify?

260
00:16:35,268 --> 00:16:38,655
Universal, Sony, and Warner. The big 3.

261
00:16:38,879 --> 00:16:42,475
Together they control roughly 70% of all streams on the platform.

262
00:16:42,764 --> 00:16:46,585
So when Spotify redistributes the demonetized track money,

263
00:16:46,938 --> 00:16:50,501
70 cents of every dollar goes to the 3 companies

264
00:16:50,694 --> 00:16:54,225
that already make more money from music than anyone else

265
00:16:54,725 --> 00:16:58,331
on Earth. Spotify didn't fight fraud. They took money from the bottom

266
00:16:58,831 --> 00:17:02,849
of the pyramid and gave it to the top. And then they called it artist-friendly?

267
00:17:03,362 --> 00:17:07,048
The independent artist, who had a song that got 800 streams last

268
00:17:07,548 --> 00:17:11,310
year, used to make about $3 from that song. Now they

269
00:17:11,358 --> 00:17:14,947
make zero. The major label artist whose song got a billion

270
00:17:14,995 --> 00:17:18,633
streams makes slightly more. The indie artist doesn't get to

271
00:17:18,649 --> 00:17:22,238
complain because, well, $3 wasn't exactly

272
00:17:22,270 --> 00:17:25,623
life-changing, was it? That's the trick. The amount per

273
00:17:25,703 --> 00:17:29,542
artist is small enough that no individual artist can justify

274
00:17:29,574 --> 00:17:32,947
hiring a lawyer. Multiply that by millions of artists,

275
00:17:33,830 --> 00:17:37,621
and you've got a massive transfer of wealth from the people who need it to

276
00:17:38,121 --> 00:17:41,379
the people who already have it. And there's a second-order effect

277
00:17:41,879 --> 00:17:45,619
that's even uglier. The 1,000-stream threshold has created

278
00:17:46,119 --> 00:17:49,859
an incentive to cheat. If you're an artist and your track is sitting at

279
00:17:50,359 --> 00:17:53,999
800 streams in November? What do you do? You buy streams.

280
00:17:54,304 --> 00:17:57,609
You hire a bot farm. You pay a service in Eastern Europe

281
00:17:58,109 --> 00:18:01,636
to push you over the line. Spotify created the demonetization rule,

282
00:18:02,230 --> 00:18:05,262
and in doing so, they created the streaming fraud industry.

283
00:18:05,535 --> 00:18:09,064
Which we'll get to in a minute. But first, let's talk about the artists

284
00:18:09,564 --> 00:18:13,284
this rule was supposed to help. The working musicians.

285
00:18:13,701 --> 00:18:17,520
The middle class of music. Because they're the ones getting squeezed

286
00:18:17,552 --> 00:18:20,986
the hardest. And they're disappearing. Here's a question.

287
00:18:21,420 --> 00:18:24,677
When was the last time a brand new artist, someone you'd never

288
00:18:24,693 --> 00:18:28,336
heard of, with no label, no TikTok viral moment,

289
00:18:28,705 --> 00:18:32,123
no industry connection, blew up on Spotify and became a star?

290
00:18:32,717 --> 00:18:36,328
Take your time, I'll wait. You're probably thinking of Chance the Rapper.

291
00:18:36,905 --> 00:18:40,404
He was the indie success story. Self-released, no label,

292
00:18:40,660 --> 00:18:43,936
won a Grammy, streaming only. That was 2016.

293
00:18:44,675 --> 00:18:48,403
Almost a decade ago. Since then? Crickets. The middle class

294
00:18:48,903 --> 00:18:52,282
of music has been hollowed out so completely that the term doesn't even apply

295
00:18:52,412 --> 00:18:56,164
anymore. There are now essentially 2 kinds of musicians on Spotify.

296
00:18:57,123 --> 00:19:00,078
At the top, you have the megastars. Taylor,

297
00:19:00,369 --> 00:19:03,991
Drake, Bad Bunny, The Weeknd, Billie. They make

298
00:19:04,491 --> 00:19:08,259
millions from streaming because they generate billions of streams. They play the

299
00:19:08,292 --> 00:19:11,085
game at a scale where the per-stream rate doesn't matter.

300
00:19:11,998 --> 00:19:15,723
Even at 3 tenths of a cent, a billion streams is $3

301
00:19:16,223 --> 00:19:19,689
million. They're fine. At the bottom, you have the hobbyists.

302
00:19:20,106 --> 00:19:24,458
People who make music in their bedrooms, upload it to Spotify via DistroKid,

303
00:19:24,698 --> 00:19:27,878
share it with their friends, and don't expect to make money.

304
00:19:28,311 --> 00:19:31,635
For them, Spotify is just a place to host their music.

305
00:19:32,069 --> 00:19:35,328
They're not trying to make a living. They're fine too. The middle is gone.

306
00:19:35,922 --> 00:19:38,234
The working musician, the person who tours,

307
00:19:38,523 --> 00:19:42,068
sells merch, has a real but modest fan base,

308
00:19:42,357 --> 00:19:45,210
maybe 20,000 to 100,000 monthly listeners.

309
00:19:45,547 --> 00:19:48,914
That person cannot survive on streaming revenue. The math doesn't work.

310
00:19:49,170 --> 00:19:52,905
Here's a real example. In 2024, an artist named

311
00:19:52,937 --> 00:19:55,631
Maria Zardoya, who fronts The Marias,

312
00:19:56,208 --> 00:19:59,799
a successful indie band with hundreds of thousands of monthly listeners,

313
00:20:00,312 --> 00:20:03,486
a Grammy nomination, real fans, real touring,

314
00:20:03,678 --> 00:20:07,528
posted her streaming numbers. Hundreds of millions of streams across

315
00:20:08,028 --> 00:20:11,267
platforms. Total revenue: enough to live on, barely,

316
00:20:11,476 --> 00:20:15,392
if you split it 4 ways between band members and a manager and an agent

317
00:20:15,472 --> 00:20:18,891
and don't count the cost of actually making the music. She's one

318
00:20:18,939 --> 00:20:22,181
of the lucky ones. She has a label. She has fans.

319
00:20:22,678 --> 00:20:26,129
She tours. Now imagine an artist with a tenth of her

320
00:20:26,209 --> 00:20:30,141
audience. 200,000 monthly listeners. That's a successful

321
00:20:30,221 --> 00:20:33,608
artist by indie standards. At 3 tenths of a cent per

322
00:20:34,108 --> 00:20:39,194
stream, 200,000 monthly listeners generating maybe 600,000

323
00:20:39,694 --> 00:20:43,433
streams a month, that's roughly $1,800. Before label cut,

324
00:20:43,946 --> 00:20:47,623
before manager cut, before agent, before taxes,

325
00:20:48,136 --> 00:20:51,668
after everyone takes their piece, the artist takes home maybe

326
00:20:52,168 --> 00:20:56,484
$600, $600 a month. From a song catalog

327
00:20:56,984 --> 00:21:00,803
that took years to build, that hundreds of thousands of people listen to

328
00:21:00,963 --> 00:21:04,401
every month. That's not a career. That's a hobby that

329
00:21:04,417 --> 00:21:07,663
happens to pay for itself. This is why the middle class of

330
00:21:07,711 --> 00:21:11,744
music is collapsing. Not because people don't care about music

331
00:21:12,244 --> 00:21:15,488
anymore. They care more than ever. Music consumption is at an

332
00:21:15,745 --> 00:21:19,938
all-time high. Spotify users stream over a billion hours of music

333
00:21:20,163 --> 00:21:23,827
every single day. People love music. They just don't pay

334
00:21:23,859 --> 00:21:27,490
for it in a way that lets musicians live. And here's the structural

335
00:21:27,990 --> 00:21:31,327
reason. In the old model— CDs, vinyl, even iTunes— if

336
00:21:31,827 --> 00:21:35,196
you bought an album, the artist got a meaningful chunk of that sale. $10 for

337
00:21:35,696 --> 00:21:39,161
a CD, the artist might get a dollar, maybe 2, but it was a

338
00:21:39,209 --> 00:21:42,467
dollar. A real dollar. A complete transaction.

339
00:21:42,885 --> 00:21:45,935
You bought the album, they got paid. In the streaming model,

340
00:21:46,432 --> 00:21:50,462
that same $10 gets split across thousands of artists

341
00:21:50,991 --> 00:21:54,443
based on what you listened to that month. If you listened to one artist

342
00:21:54,603 --> 00:21:57,873
all month, That artist gets your share of the pool.

343
00:21:58,706 --> 00:22:03,016
If you listen to 1,000, each one gets a sliver. The artist

344
00:22:03,516 --> 00:22:06,637
who made your favorite album of the year? They get fractions of a cent from

345
00:22:06,701 --> 00:22:09,906
you, even though you love their work. Because the system doesn't

346
00:22:09,922 --> 00:22:13,735
care what you love. It cares what you played. And the industry knows

347
00:22:13,831 --> 00:22:16,747
this. That's why tours have gotten more expensive.

348
00:22:17,036 --> 00:22:20,689
Why merch costs more. Why artists sell

349
00:22:20,817 --> 00:22:23,989
their catalogs for hundreds of millions to private equity.

350
00:22:24,262 --> 00:22:28,000
Streaming doesn't pay, so every other revenue stream has

351
00:22:28,032 --> 00:22:31,402
to compensate. The concert ticket that used to cost $40

352
00:22:31,883 --> 00:22:35,317
now costs $120 because the artist can't

353
00:22:35,817 --> 00:22:39,008
make rent from Spotify plays. You think Ticketmaster is the

354
00:22:39,024 --> 00:22:43,003
bad guy. And they are. But Ticketmaster is a symptom. Spotify is

355
00:22:43,051 --> 00:22:47,015
the disease. When the world's largest music platform pays

356
00:22:47,143 --> 00:22:49,598
artists 3/10 of a cent per stream,

357
00:22:50,160 --> 00:22:53,898
every other part of the music industry has to extract more

358
00:22:54,011 --> 00:22:57,687
from you to make up the difference. The middle class of music is dying

359
00:22:57,720 --> 00:23:00,788
in front of us. Quietly. Without protest.

360
00:23:01,174 --> 00:23:05,078
Because the artist who would protest can't afford to take a year off to organize.

361
00:23:05,592 --> 00:23:09,030
They're too busy trying to pay rent. And Spotify's response?

362
00:23:09,769 --> 00:23:13,657
They raised the price of Premium again. And introduced a new feature

363
00:23:13,866 --> 00:23:17,272
called, I'm not making this up, AI DJ. But before

364
00:23:17,320 --> 00:23:21,112
we get to the AI slop, let's talk about the fraud economy Spotify's

365
00:23:21,241 --> 00:23:25,539
own rules created. Because that's the next domino. In January 2024,

366
00:23:26,084 --> 00:23:30,044
Spotify removed a song called Heat of the Moment by an artist named

367
00:23:30,140 --> 00:23:33,651
Antonio Lulic. Or rather, they removed billions of streams from

368
00:23:33,683 --> 00:23:37,482
him. Specifically, they accused him of using bots to

369
00:23:37,530 --> 00:23:41,586
inflate his play counts and stripped him of around 700

370
00:23:41,602 --> 00:23:45,529
million streams. He wasn't alone. In late 2023 and

371
00:23:45,545 --> 00:23:49,216
throughout 2024, Spotify went on a purge.

372
00:23:49,312 --> 00:23:53,223
They removed millions of tracks and billions of streams from artists they

373
00:23:53,239 --> 00:23:57,184
accused of streaming fraud. They published a loud-and-clear report claiming

374
00:23:57,232 --> 00:24:00,952
they'd identified and stopped hundreds of millions of dollars in fraudulent

375
00:24:01,016 --> 00:24:03,742
payouts. Sounds great, right?

376
00:24:04,704 --> 00:24:07,799
Spotify fighting fraud. Protecting artists wrong.

377
00:24:08,376 --> 00:24:12,433
Here's the part they don't put in the press release: Spotify created

378
00:24:12,481 --> 00:24:16,522
the fraud problem. The fraud exists because Spotify's payout system

379
00:24:16,570 --> 00:24:19,985
rewards streams above all else. If streams are money,

380
00:24:20,242 --> 00:24:23,431
then fake streams are fake money. And fake money

381
00:24:23,528 --> 00:24:27,229
is, in any system with a leak, going to be manufactured. The bot

382
00:24:27,729 --> 00:24:31,314
farm industry is now worth an estimated hundreds of millions of dollars per

383
00:24:31,814 --> 00:24:35,448
year. There are services, legal services, operating openly,

384
00:24:36,024 --> 00:24:40,094
advertising on Google, that will sell you 10,000 Spotify streams

385
00:24:40,286 --> 00:24:43,699
for around $10. They use networks of compromised

386
00:24:43,731 --> 00:24:47,704
devices, fake accounts, and residential IP proxies

387
00:24:47,816 --> 00:24:51,181
to generate streams that look real to Spotify's detection

388
00:24:51,681 --> 00:24:55,475
systems. An artist who's 800 streams short of the demonetization

389
00:24:55,587 --> 00:24:59,497
threshold can pay $15 and cross the line. A label

390
00:24:59,997 --> 00:25:03,808
trying to push a new single up the charts can buy half a million streams

391
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:07,573
for a few thousand dollars and trigger algorithmic momentum

392
00:25:07,669 --> 00:25:10,746
that generates real streams. This isn't a fringe

393
00:25:10,794 --> 00:25:14,031
problem. Spotify themselves estimated that somewhere

394
00:25:14,095 --> 00:25:17,668
between 2 and 4% of all streams on the platform are

395
00:25:17,765 --> 00:25:20,751
fake. That's billions of streams per month.

396
00:25:21,152 --> 00:25:23,915
And the actual number is almost certainly higher.

397
00:25:24,188 --> 00:25:27,979
Because Spotify's detection is— charitably— mediocre.

398
00:25:28,285 --> 00:25:31,481
Independent analyses have put the fraud rate closer to 10%.

399
00:25:32,541 --> 00:25:35,754
Here's what that means in dollar terms. If Spotify pays

400
00:25:36,254 --> 00:25:39,947
out around $9 billion a year to rights holders, and even

401
00:25:40,447 --> 00:25:44,701
5% of streams are fraudulent, that's roughly $450

402
00:25:45,201 --> 00:25:48,745
million per year. Going to fake artists, fake labels,

403
00:25:48,937 --> 00:25:53,026
and the bot farms that serve them. $450 million that

404
00:25:53,526 --> 00:25:56,378
should've gone to real musicians making real music.

405
00:25:57,019 --> 00:26:00,483
And here's the kicker: that money comes out of the same revenue

406
00:26:00,983 --> 00:26:04,026
share pool as everyone else's. Every fake stream

407
00:26:04,526 --> 00:26:08,163
is a fraction of a cent stolen from a real artist. When a bot farm

408
00:26:08,663 --> 00:26:11,996
generates a million streams for a fake artist, that million

409
00:26:12,028 --> 00:26:15,911
streams' worth of money is deducted from the pool that would have gone

410
00:26:16,024 --> 00:26:18,833
to legitimate artists. Spotify knows this.

411
00:26:19,251 --> 00:26:22,992
They've known it for years. They periodically announce crackdowns,

412
00:26:23,329 --> 00:26:26,540
like the 2024 purge, to make it look

413
00:26:27,040 --> 00:26:30,474
like they're doing something. But the structural problem is theirs to

414
00:26:30,974 --> 00:26:35,226
solve, and they haven't solved it because solving it would require either

415
00:26:35,726 --> 00:26:39,529
dramatically improving their detection technology, which costs money,

416
00:26:39,866 --> 00:26:44,577
or fundamentally changing the payout model away from pure per-stream

417
00:26:44,769 --> 00:26:48,679
revenue share, which would upset the major labels who benefit

418
00:26:49,179 --> 00:26:52,941
from the current system. So instead, they publish an annual report,

419
00:26:53,101 --> 00:26:56,754
purge a few scapegoats, and move on. There's another layer to this.

420
00:26:57,604 --> 00:27:00,920
Some of the streaming fraud isn't even fraud. It's just

421
00:27:01,033 --> 00:27:04,862
artists asking their fans to stream their music. Spotify's terms

422
00:27:04,878 --> 00:27:09,110
of service prohibit artificial streaming, But the line between artificial

423
00:27:09,126 --> 00:27:12,541
and organic is blurry. If an artist tells their fans

424
00:27:12,573 --> 00:27:16,405
to put their album on repeat while they sleep, is that artificial?

425
00:27:17,047 --> 00:27:20,895
If a fan runs a playlist on shuffle for 16 hours a day to support

426
00:27:21,395 --> 00:27:24,310
their favorite band, is that artificial? Spotify says yes,

427
00:27:24,615 --> 00:27:28,495
sometimes. They've flagged legitimate fan streaming as fraud

428
00:27:28,671 --> 00:27:32,808
and pulled royalties from artists who did nothing wrong. So you have real

429
00:27:32,856 --> 00:27:36,944
fraud going unpunished at scale, Real artists being punished

430
00:27:37,444 --> 00:27:41,142
for fake fraud, and a payout system that incentivizes the whole

431
00:27:41,254 --> 00:27:44,555
mess. Spotify's response is to raise prices and

432
00:27:44,699 --> 00:27:48,416
add AI features. We're gonna talk about those AI features next.

433
00:27:48,945 --> 00:27:51,445
Because they are something else. Every single day,

434
00:27:52,021 --> 00:27:55,787
Spotify adds over 100,000 new tracks to its catalog.

435
00:27:56,075 --> 00:27:59,296
100,000. Every day. That's more than one new

436
00:27:59,796 --> 00:28:03,061
song per second. 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.

437
00:28:03,446 --> 00:28:07,003
Do you know how many of those songs are made by humans playing instruments in

438
00:28:07,067 --> 00:28:10,689
rooms? Nobody does. Spotify doesn't track

439
00:28:11,189 --> 00:28:14,887
it. But independent estimates suggest that somewhere between 20% and 40%

440
00:28:15,160 --> 00:28:19,166
of new uploads are now generated, at least in part, by AI.

441
00:28:19,871 --> 00:28:23,508
Either fully AI-generated music, AI-assisted music

442
00:28:23,653 --> 00:28:27,675
where the human role is essentially pressing generate, or AI-modified

443
00:28:28,175 --> 00:28:31,349
existing music— sped up, Slowed down, remixed,

444
00:28:31,574 --> 00:28:35,157
uploaded under fake artist names to siphon streams. Here's how the scam

445
00:28:35,205 --> 00:28:39,382
works. Someone, usually operating out of a country with low labor

446
00:28:39,882 --> 00:28:43,865
costs, uses an AI music generator like Suno or Udio to produce

447
00:28:44,365 --> 00:28:47,641
hundreds of songs per day. These songs are not good. They're not meant

448
00:28:48,141 --> 00:28:51,320
to be good. They're meant to be just good enough to slip into a mood

449
00:28:51,352 --> 00:28:53,907
playlist. Lo-fi study beats.

450
00:28:54,630 --> 00:28:58,710
Focus instrumental. Sleep sounds. Chill acoustic background.

451
00:28:59,224 --> 00:29:01,617
You've seen these playlists, you've probably listened to them.

452
00:29:02,500 --> 00:29:06,436
You didn't notice the artist names because you weren't paying attention. You just

453
00:29:06,936 --> 00:29:10,820
wanted something in the background while you worked. The operator uploads

454
00:29:11,013 --> 00:29:14,258
all 100 songs to Spotify under different fake artist

455
00:29:14,306 --> 00:29:17,550
names. They create their own playlists, or pay

456
00:29:17,614 --> 00:29:21,325
for placement on existing ones, and slot their AI tracks into

457
00:29:21,825 --> 00:29:25,559
the rotation. Then they sit back and collect fractions of a cent per stream.

458
00:29:25,960 --> 00:29:29,905
Multiplied by thousands of tracks, multiplied by millions

459
00:29:30,405 --> 00:29:34,042
of playlist listeners. At scale, this is real money. A single

460
00:29:34,122 --> 00:29:37,971
operator running 50 fake artist accounts, each generating

461
00:29:38,035 --> 00:29:41,274
100,000 streams per month, is making something

462
00:29:41,338 --> 00:29:44,738
like $7,500 a month. Per operator.

463
00:29:45,347 --> 00:29:48,683
There are now thousands of these operators. The economics are too good to ignore.

464
00:29:49,052 --> 00:29:52,482
And it gets worse. Spotify itself has been caught

465
00:29:52,982 --> 00:29:56,794
doing this. In 2024, multiple investigations

466
00:29:56,810 --> 00:30:00,561
revealed that Spotify's own editorial playlists, the ones

467
00:30:00,657 --> 00:30:03,719
curated by Spotify staff, the ones that can make or

468
00:30:03,799 --> 00:30:08,095
break a real artist's career, were stuffed with tracks from so-called

469
00:30:08,272 --> 00:30:12,023
ghost artists. Artists with no online presence, no social

470
00:30:12,055 --> 00:30:15,421
media, no concerts, no photos, no biography.

471
00:30:15,726 --> 00:30:18,964
Just a name, a generic profile picture, and dozens of

472
00:30:19,012 --> 00:30:22,734
tracks pumping into playlists with millions of followers. Why would Spotify

473
00:30:22,878 --> 00:30:26,378
do this? Because they pay themselves for those streams.

474
00:30:26,875 --> 00:30:30,407
The tracks are uploaded through distributors that Spotify either

475
00:30:30,568 --> 00:30:34,693
owns or has financial relationships with. When Spotify's

476
00:30:35,193 --> 00:30:39,060
editorial team places a ghost artist track in a flagship playlist,

477
00:30:39,253 --> 00:30:42,881
the payout for that stream goes back to Spotify's bottom

478
00:30:42,929 --> 00:30:47,039
line. They're laundering their own royalty payments. Spotify denied this,

479
00:30:47,199 --> 00:30:50,615
of course. They said the artists were real, just private.

480
00:30:50,887 --> 00:30:54,766
They said the tracks were licensed. They refused to name the artists.

481
00:30:55,039 --> 00:30:58,149
They refused to provide evidence. They just denied,

482
00:30:58,726 --> 00:31:02,878
and then quietly removed some of the most obvious offenders from their playlists,

483
00:31:02,990 --> 00:31:06,404
and waited for the story to die. The result of all of this

484
00:31:06,853 --> 00:31:10,588
is that Spotify is, increasingly, not a music streaming

485
00:31:10,668 --> 00:31:13,987
service. It's an AI slop distribution platform

486
00:31:14,211 --> 00:31:18,411
with a music streaming service attached. The real artists are competing

487
00:31:18,523 --> 00:31:21,795
for attention against an infinite flood of machine-generated

488
00:31:21,827 --> 00:31:25,484
noise. The payout pool is being drained by bad actors.

489
00:31:25,917 --> 00:31:29,093
The editorial playlists that used to be a path to discovery

490
00:31:29,206 --> 00:31:32,879
for real artists are increasingly populated by ghost

491
00:31:33,379 --> 00:31:37,146
tracks. And here's the most insidious part. The flood of new tracks,

492
00:31:37,451 --> 00:31:40,755
100,000 per day, mostly garbage, is used

493
00:31:41,255 --> 00:31:44,814
by Spotify as a marketing talking point. Over 100,000 new

494
00:31:44,862 --> 00:31:48,279
songs added every day, they say. The largest catalog

495
00:31:48,295 --> 00:31:51,744
in music history. Yes. The largest catalog in music

496
00:31:52,244 --> 00:31:56,171
history. Most of it trash. Most of it not made by humans.

497
00:31:56,396 --> 00:32:00,823
Most of it never listened to by anyone. You're paying for that. Your subscription

498
00:32:00,888 --> 00:32:05,283
fee is paying for the storage, the bandwidth, the algorithmic overhead

499
00:32:05,783 --> 00:32:09,342
of cataloging and processing 100,000 new songs per day,

500
00:32:09,775 --> 00:32:13,384
of which maybe 1% will ever be played by a real

501
00:32:13,400 --> 00:32:16,579
person. The other 99% is digital pollution.

502
00:32:17,398 --> 00:32:20,673
And Spotify counts it as a feature. If that makes you angry,

503
00:32:20,946 --> 00:32:25,121
wait until you hear what they spent a billion dollars on next. In February

504
00:32:25,621 --> 00:32:29,713
2019, Spotify bought Gimlet Media for $230

505
00:32:30,213 --> 00:32:33,823
million. And Anchor, a podcast hosting platform,

506
00:32:34,032 --> 00:32:37,757
for $150 million. Total: just

507
00:32:37,805 --> 00:32:41,320
under $400 million. In one day to

508
00:32:41,416 --> 00:32:44,737
enter the podcast business. This was the start of what would become a

509
00:32:44,850 --> 00:32:48,700
billion-dollar bet. Over the next 4 years, Spotify spent

510
00:32:48,796 --> 00:32:52,229
over a billion dollars acquiring podcast companies and

511
00:32:52,261 --> 00:32:56,032
signing exclusive deals. They bought The Ringer from Bill Simmons

512
00:32:56,256 --> 00:32:59,754
for nearly $200 million. They signed

513
00:32:59,786 --> 00:33:03,604
Joe Rogan to a multi-year exclusive deal reportedly worth

514
00:33:03,780 --> 00:33:07,213
over $200 million. Later renewed for a reported

515
00:33:07,326 --> 00:33:10,871
$250 million. They signed

516
00:33:10,919 --> 00:33:14,256
Meghan Markle to a deal reportedly worth $20 million,

517
00:33:14,785 --> 00:33:18,683
which produced 12 episodes and then collapsed in mutual recrimination.

518
00:33:19,518 --> 00:33:22,373
They signed the Obamas. They signed Kim Kardashian.

519
00:33:22,886 --> 00:33:26,159
They bought Parcast. They bought Megaphone. They built a

520
00:33:26,659 --> 00:33:30,442
podcast empire. The strategy made sense on paper. Spotify wanted

521
00:33:30,942 --> 00:33:34,418
to be the default audio platform. Not just music— audio.

522
00:33:34,515 --> 00:33:38,377
And podcasts had something music didn't: music royalties ate

523
00:33:38,877 --> 00:33:42,238
most of the revenue. Podcasts were much cheaper. If Spotify

524
00:33:42,511 --> 00:33:45,940
owned the podcast, they didn't have to share the revenue with labels.

525
00:33:46,213 --> 00:33:49,466
They could keep it all. And podcasts had something else:

526
00:33:49,898 --> 00:33:53,247
they were engaged. People who listened to podcasts listened for

527
00:33:53,488 --> 00:33:57,189
hours per week. Habitual, loyal, captivated. If Spotify

528
00:33:57,689 --> 00:34:00,475
could own that engagement, they'd own the listener. So they spent.

529
00:34:00,860 --> 00:34:04,066
And spent. And spent. And it didn't work.

530
00:34:04,723 --> 00:34:08,699
Here's what happened. Joe Rogan's exclusive deal drove some listeners

531
00:34:08,731 --> 00:34:12,306
to Spotify. But many of his fans, the ones who already used

532
00:34:12,482 --> 00:34:16,185
Apple Podcasts or other apps, resented being forced to switch.

533
00:34:16,906 --> 00:34:20,000
A meaningful chunk of his audience just stopped listening rather

534
00:34:20,016 --> 00:34:23,767
than migrate. And then, when Spotify's exclusivity

535
00:34:23,864 --> 00:34:27,585
period ended, and Rogan went back to being available everywhere,

536
00:34:27,954 --> 00:34:31,212
the supposed benefit of the exclusive deal evaporated.

537
00:34:31,645 --> 00:34:35,882
Spotify paid a quarter of a billion dollars for temporary exclusivity

538
00:34:36,075 --> 00:34:40,152
that didn't even last the full contract. Meghan Markle's deal produced

539
00:34:40,652 --> 00:34:43,458
a single season of a podcast called Archetypes,

540
00:34:43,779 --> 00:34:47,358
which got middling reviews and then was unceremoniously

541
00:34:47,454 --> 00:34:51,065
dumped when the deal fell apart. She and Spotify's executive

542
00:34:51,565 --> 00:34:54,662
allegedly didn't get along. A Spotify executive publicly

543
00:34:54,678 --> 00:34:58,197
called her and Harry grifters. That's a Spotify executive

544
00:34:58,872 --> 00:35:02,294
talking about Spotify's own signing. That's how well that

545
00:35:02,407 --> 00:35:06,167
billion dollars was spent. The ringer has been successful in some

546
00:35:06,667 --> 00:35:10,698
respects. Bill Simmons is a shrewd operator. But it hasn't moved the

547
00:35:11,198 --> 00:35:14,650
needle for Spotify's bottom line. Gimlet, which was supposed

548
00:35:14,682 --> 00:35:17,687
to be the HBO of podcasts, has been largely gutted.

549
00:35:18,008 --> 00:35:22,021
Several of their flagship shows were canceled, Talented producers left.

550
00:35:22,550 --> 00:35:26,140
The promise of high-quality narrative podcasting was sacrificed

551
00:35:26,316 --> 00:35:30,179
on the altar of engagement metrics. And then, there's the broader

552
00:35:30,679 --> 00:35:34,169
strategic failure. Spotify tried to make podcasting work

553
00:35:34,669 --> 00:35:37,311
the way music works— centralized, algorithmic,

554
00:35:37,808 --> 00:35:41,221
exclusive. But podcasting was built on RSS— open,

555
00:35:41,478 --> 00:35:44,555
distributed, platform-agnostic. Listeners had a habit of

556
00:35:44,587 --> 00:35:47,488
using whatever app they preferred. Apple Podcasts,

557
00:35:47,713 --> 00:35:51,367
Overcast, Pocket Casts. They didn't want to be locked into Spotify.

558
00:35:51,880 --> 00:35:55,375
And creators didn't want to be locked in either. The Joe Rogan

559
00:35:55,423 --> 00:35:59,126
exclusivity backfired because creators saw what happened

560
00:35:59,174 --> 00:36:02,476
when you signed with Spotify. You got paid, but you lost

561
00:36:02,976 --> 00:36:07,045
your audience. By 2023, Spotify was quietly retreating

562
00:36:07,109 --> 00:36:11,052
from podcasting. They canceled shows. They laid off staff,

563
00:36:11,212 --> 00:36:14,226
including a significant portion of their podcast division.

564
00:36:14,579 --> 00:36:18,076
They shut down Parcast. They took shows off exclusive.

565
00:36:18,414 --> 00:36:21,496
They restructured their deals. They wrote down the value of

566
00:36:21,544 --> 00:36:24,563
their podcast acquisitions. Meaning, in plain

567
00:36:24,691 --> 00:36:29,203
English, they admitted they overpaid. Here's the brutal truth: Spotify

568
00:36:29,703 --> 00:36:33,763
spent over a billion dollars to enter a business that, even at its peak,

569
00:36:34,164 --> 00:36:37,231
contributed only a small fraction of their revenue.

570
00:36:37,375 --> 00:36:41,180
The podcast business still doesn't generate meaningful profit

571
00:36:41,213 --> 00:36:44,889
for Spotify. And in the process, they alienated listeners

572
00:36:44,921 --> 00:36:48,678
who didn't want to switch apps, alienated creators who didn't

573
00:36:48,694 --> 00:36:51,970
want to be locked in, and burned through capital that could have

574
00:36:51,986 --> 00:36:55,213
gone to— oh, I don't know— paying artists

575
00:36:55,342 --> 00:36:58,890
more. But the billion dollars is gone. The shows

576
00:36:59,390 --> 00:37:02,952
are canceled. The deals have been restructured. And Spotify has

577
00:37:03,048 --> 00:37:05,922
moved on to their next pivot: audiobooks. Oh,

578
00:37:06,340 --> 00:37:09,888
audiobooks. Where do I even start with audiobooks? In late

579
00:37:10,388 --> 00:37:14,095
2023, Spotify announced that Premium subscribers would get

580
00:37:14,595 --> 00:37:18,220
15 hours of audiobooks per month included with their subscription.

581
00:37:18,559 --> 00:37:21,894
Great news, right? Audible charges $15 a

582
00:37:22,394 --> 00:37:26,086
month for one credit. Spotify is throwing audiobooks into your existing

583
00:37:26,118 --> 00:37:29,766
subscription. What's not to like? Here's what's not to like:

584
00:37:30,152 --> 00:37:34,250
15 hours. Per month. That's it. A typical audiobook

585
00:37:34,282 --> 00:37:37,866
is 10 to 15 hours. So you get one audiobook per

586
00:37:38,366 --> 00:37:42,192
month, maybe 2 short ones if you're lucky. After that, you have to buy more,

587
00:37:42,561 --> 00:37:45,709
and the buying more is where it gets ugly. When you run out of your

588
00:37:45,757 --> 00:37:49,194
15 hours, Spotify prompts you to buy more hours.

589
00:37:49,531 --> 00:37:52,229
They sell 10-hour top-ups for around $13,

590
00:37:53,144 --> 00:37:56,854
which is, conveniently, almost exactly what Audible charges for

591
00:37:57,354 --> 00:38:00,837
a credit. So Spotify didn't replace Audible. They created a

592
00:38:00,853 --> 00:38:04,418
worse Audible, with a worse selection, baked into your music

593
00:38:04,918 --> 00:38:09,103
subscription. But here's the real trick. The reason Spotify added

594
00:38:09,199 --> 00:38:12,612
audiobooks wasn't to give you a feature. It was to justify

595
00:38:12,805 --> 00:38:18,365
the price hike. Remember the April 2024 hike? From $10.99

596
00:38:18,590 --> 00:38:22,804
to $11.99? Spotify explicitly cited

597
00:38:22,916 --> 00:38:26,522
the inclusion of audiobooks as the reason. They added a feature

598
00:38:27,022 --> 00:38:30,865
most users don't use, and then used that feature as the justification to

599
00:38:31,009 --> 00:38:34,618
raise prices on everyone. Including the people who don't use

600
00:38:35,118 --> 00:38:38,872
it. It's a textbook bundling trick. You add a low-value component

601
00:38:39,372 --> 00:38:42,773
to a bundle, raise the price of the bundle, and pocket the difference

602
00:38:43,273 --> 00:38:47,348
from the users who never use the new component. Most Spotify subscribers

603
00:38:47,685 --> 00:38:50,880
don't listen to audiobooks. Spotify knows this.

604
00:38:51,955 --> 00:38:55,535
But they get to charge everyone an extra dollar or 2 per month because

605
00:38:55,567 --> 00:38:58,762
the feature is included. And the audiobook selection

606
00:38:58,794 --> 00:39:03,092
itself is rough. Spotify has around 250,000

607
00:39:03,252 --> 00:39:06,538
audiobooks. Audible has over 700,000.

608
00:39:07,099 --> 00:39:10,930
The Spotify catalog is missing huge numbers of major titles.

609
00:39:11,283 --> 00:39:14,649
You'll search for a book you want, find it's not there, and be told

610
00:39:15,149 --> 00:39:18,753
to either buy it separately at full retail price, or wait for Spotify

611
00:39:18,977 --> 00:39:22,440
to maybe add it eventually. And the authors are getting screwed too.

612
00:39:22,841 --> 00:39:26,255
In 2024, the Authors Guild and several prominent

613
00:39:26,415 --> 00:39:29,974
authors filed formal complaints against Spotify

614
00:39:30,343 --> 00:39:34,256
over the audiobook bundling. The issue was this: Spotify was

615
00:39:34,288 --> 00:39:38,186
paying audiobook royalties based on a formula that essentially

616
00:39:38,218 --> 00:39:41,843
treated audiobook listening as a fraction of total listening time,

617
00:39:42,308 --> 00:39:45,821
similar to how music royalties work. But audiobooks

618
00:39:45,901 --> 00:39:49,430
aren't music. A typical audiobook listener spends hours

619
00:39:49,446 --> 00:39:52,735
on a single book. The way Spotify's payout math worked,

620
00:39:52,959 --> 00:39:57,306
authors were getting fractions of a cent per hour of listening, which translated

621
00:39:57,806 --> 00:40:01,931
to tiny, tiny payouts. For a book that took an author years

622
00:40:01,963 --> 00:40:05,418
to write, and that the audiobook narrator spent weeks

623
00:40:05,918 --> 00:40:09,017
recording, the royalty payout under Spotify's system might

624
00:40:09,517 --> 00:40:12,761
be a few dollars for thousands of listening hours. Audible pays

625
00:40:12,954 --> 00:40:16,232
authors a flat, credit-based royalty that's much more generous.

626
00:40:16,602 --> 00:40:20,008
Spotify's system is by comparison an insult. And there's another

627
00:40:20,024 --> 00:40:22,917
wrinkle. Spotify acquired Findaway,

628
00:40:23,254 --> 00:40:26,881
an audiobook distribution platform, in 2022. That gave

629
00:40:26,929 --> 00:40:30,807
them access to a huge catalog of audiobooks. But it also gave

630
00:40:31,307 --> 00:40:34,124
them leverage to dictate terms to authors and narrators.

631
00:40:34,461 --> 00:40:37,922
Findaway narrators, who are paid a flat fee to record books,

632
00:40:38,627 --> 00:40:41,961
found that their work was being used to drive Spotify

633
00:40:42,025 --> 00:40:45,422
subscriptions without any meaningful additional compensation.

634
00:40:45,935 --> 00:40:49,589
The narrator who spent 40 hours recording a book might see $10

635
00:40:50,118 --> 00:40:53,739
in additional royalties from Spotify's bundling, while Spotify

636
00:40:53,851 --> 00:40:57,267
used their work as a marketing talking point to justify

637
00:40:57,459 --> 00:41:01,297
a price hike. So let's recap. Spotify added

638
00:41:01,473 --> 00:41:05,471
audiobooks to justify a price increase. Most subscribers don't

639
00:41:05,504 --> 00:41:08,843
use the audiobook feature. The audiobook selection is much

640
00:41:08,859 --> 00:41:12,858
smaller than Audible's. Authors get paid less under Spotify's system

641
00:41:13,130 --> 00:41:16,438
than under Audible's. Narrators get paid almost

642
00:41:16,938 --> 00:41:20,260
nothing extra. And Spotify gets to keep the additional revenue from

643
00:41:20,276 --> 00:41:23,294
the price hike bundling. They call it bundling.

644
00:41:24,370 --> 00:41:27,949
I have a different word for it. But you've probably noticed something.

645
00:41:28,527 --> 00:41:31,914
I keep mentioning that Spotify still doesn't have lossless audio.

646
00:41:32,219 --> 00:41:35,301
Let's talk about that broken promise next. Because it's been

647
00:41:35,366 --> 00:41:37,725
5 years. In February 2021,

648
00:41:38,014 --> 00:41:41,225
Spotify announced Spotify HiFi. The pitch was

649
00:41:41,725 --> 00:41:45,687
simple: lossless, CD-quality audio for premium subscribers.

650
00:41:46,105 --> 00:41:49,299
Higher bitrate, better sound, no compression artifacts.

651
00:41:49,556 --> 00:41:52,832
Coming later in 2021. It's 2026.

652
00:41:53,169 --> 00:41:56,638
HiFi still doesn't exist. 5 years. 5 years

653
00:41:57,138 --> 00:42:00,877
of a promised feature that has never shipped. Spotify has mentioned HiFi in

654
00:42:00,957 --> 00:42:04,201
exactly zero product launches since the original

655
00:42:04,249 --> 00:42:08,135
announcement. They've removed references to it from their website.

656
00:42:08,183 --> 00:42:11,411
They've stopped responding to questions about it. Their customer

657
00:42:11,911 --> 00:42:15,409
support, when asked, gives vague non-answers like,

658
00:42:15,425 --> 00:42:19,311
we're still exploring options. In the same 5 years that Spotify

659
00:42:19,423 --> 00:42:22,619
has failed to ship lossless audio, Apple Music shipped it.

660
00:42:23,116 --> 00:42:25,910
For free. Included in the standard subscription.

661
00:42:26,263 --> 00:42:29,475
No extra charge. Tidal built their entire brand

662
00:42:29,975 --> 00:42:33,328
around it. Amazon Music Unlimited added it at no extra cost.

663
00:42:33,553 --> 00:42:37,358
YouTube Music added it. Qobuz has had it for a decade. Every major

664
00:42:37,407 --> 00:42:41,437
music streaming service on Earth offers lossless audio. Except Spotify.

665
00:42:41,822 --> 00:42:45,547
Why? Here's the honest answer: Spotify can't afford to ship

666
00:42:46,047 --> 00:42:48,962
it. Not because lossless audio is expensive. It isn't,

667
00:42:48,978 --> 00:42:51,799
not really. The bandwidth costs are manageable.

668
00:42:51,943 --> 00:42:55,935
But because Spotify's entire infrastructure was built around aggressive

669
00:42:56,095 --> 00:42:59,542
audio compression. Their Ogg Vorbis codec at 96

670
00:43:00,042 --> 00:43:04,062
to 320 kilobits per second was designed to minimize bandwidth costs

671
00:43:04,562 --> 00:43:07,893
at scale. Serving billions of streams per day at 320

672
00:43:08,393 --> 00:43:11,981
kilobits per second costs them a certain amount of money. Serving those same streams

673
00:43:12,481 --> 00:43:15,796
at 1.4 megabits, CD quality, would cost them roughly

674
00:43:15,812 --> 00:43:19,402
4 times as much in bandwidth. And Spotify operates on thin

675
00:43:19,434 --> 00:43:23,408
margins. Or at least, they claim to. The other reason is

676
00:43:23,520 --> 00:43:27,045
strategic. Spotify's not stupid. They know

677
00:43:27,061 --> 00:43:30,603
that if they ship lossless audio, they need to either charge more

678
00:43:30,715 --> 00:43:34,705
for it, which would mean another price hike, which would mean another round

679
00:43:34,737 --> 00:43:38,006
of bad press, or include it in the existing plan,

680
00:43:38,342 --> 00:43:41,963
which would mean absorbing the bandwidth cost. So they've stalled.

681
00:43:42,428 --> 00:43:46,005
They announced HiFi in 2021, to keep up with Apple's

682
00:43:46,037 --> 00:43:49,202
announcement that Apple Music was going lossless.

683
00:43:49,572 --> 00:43:52,914
They never had to ship it because their subscribers didn't

684
00:43:52,946 --> 00:43:56,545
leave in meaningful numbers. Most people can't tell the

685
00:43:56,561 --> 00:44:00,370
difference between 320 kbps and lossless on

686
00:44:00,418 --> 00:44:04,033
Bluetooth earbuds anyway. So Spotify quietly killed

687
00:44:04,533 --> 00:44:07,504
the project and never told anyone. But the promise is still out there.

688
00:44:08,130 --> 00:44:11,455
The 2021 announcement is still in archives. People still

689
00:44:11,648 --> 00:44:14,358
ask about HiFi in Spotify community forums.

690
00:44:14,727 --> 00:44:18,319
Spotify still ignores them. 5 years. This is the kind of

691
00:44:18,819 --> 00:44:22,681
small, specific, infuriating failure that defines modern Spotify.

692
00:44:23,355 --> 00:44:26,995
It's not a single catastrophic mistake. It's a thousand small ones.

693
00:44:27,220 --> 00:44:31,357
A promised feature that never shipped. A price hike that wasn't justified.

694
00:44:31,485 --> 00:44:35,398
A royalty cut disguised as fraud prevention. A podcast

695
00:44:35,898 --> 00:44:39,039
empire that collapsed. An audiobook pivot that nobody asked for.

696
00:44:39,473 --> 00:44:42,504
Each one, in isolation, is a minor story.

697
00:44:42,761 --> 00:44:46,226
Together they form a pattern. And the pattern is this: Spotify

698
00:44:46,290 --> 00:44:50,252
takes more from you, gives less to artists, and invests the difference

699
00:44:50,300 --> 00:44:54,086
in whatever the next big pivot is supposed to be. Podcasts,

700
00:44:54,311 --> 00:44:57,695
audiobooks, AI. Anything except the core product,

701
00:44:57,759 --> 00:45:01,016
the music app you pay for, but maybe you don't care about hi-fi.

702
00:45:01,946 --> 00:45:05,798
Maybe you don't care about podcasts. Maybe you just want to know why

703
00:45:06,298 --> 00:45:09,748
your Discover Weekly has gotten worse. Let's talk about

704
00:45:09,797 --> 00:45:13,105
that. When was the last time Discover Weekly introduced you

705
00:45:13,605 --> 00:45:16,686
to an artist you'd never heard of, who you actually loved,

706
00:45:16,798 --> 00:45:20,218
who you then went and followed, and whose music you then sought out on

707
00:45:20,315 --> 00:45:23,591
your own? Take your time. For most of you, the answer is,

708
00:45:24,185 --> 00:45:27,380
I can't remember. Maybe years ago. Maybe never.

709
00:45:27,702 --> 00:45:31,459
Here's why. When Discover Weekly launched in 2015,

710
00:45:31,716 --> 00:45:35,249
It was genuinely magical. The algorithm would analyze your

711
00:45:35,749 --> 00:45:39,664
listening history, find patterns, and recommend songs from artists

712
00:45:40,164 --> 00:45:44,192
you'd never heard but who matched your taste. People would post their Discover

713
00:45:44,256 --> 00:45:47,949
Weekly on social media. It was a feature. A real feature.

714
00:45:48,367 --> 00:45:51,016
Something Spotify did that nobody else could do.

715
00:45:51,305 --> 00:45:55,078
Fast forward to 2026. Discover Weekly is mostly the

716
00:45:55,578 --> 00:45:58,654
same songs you already listen to, Slightly remixed,

717
00:45:58,864 --> 00:46:02,955
with one or two unfamiliar tracks buried at the bottom. Release Radar

718
00:46:03,165 --> 00:46:06,819
is dominated by major label releases. Your daily mixes have

719
00:46:06,867 --> 00:46:09,602
devolved into the same 50 songs on rotation.

720
00:46:09,893 --> 00:46:13,987
Spotify's algorithmic recommendations have, by almost every user's

721
00:46:14,068 --> 00:46:18,215
anecdotal experience, gotten worse. Why? Here's the structural

722
00:46:18,263 --> 00:46:22,226
reason: Spotify's recommendation algorithm isn't purely

723
00:46:22,726 --> 00:46:26,884
designed to find you new music you'd love. It's designed to maximize total

724
00:46:26,980 --> 00:46:30,882
listening time. Those sound like the same goal. They're not.

725
00:46:31,091 --> 00:46:34,816
If Spotify wanted to find you new music you'd love, they'd recommend

726
00:46:34,928 --> 00:46:38,637
unfamiliar tracks and accept that some of those wouldn't click,

727
00:46:39,167 --> 00:46:42,555
leading you to skip, leading to a temporary dip in engagement.

728
00:46:42,957 --> 00:46:46,377
They don't do that. Instead, the algorithm plays it safe.

729
00:46:46,826 --> 00:46:50,951
It recommends tracks similar to what you already listen to, Because those

730
00:46:50,983 --> 00:46:54,333
tracks have a high probability of being played through

731
00:46:54,509 --> 00:46:58,404
to the end. More plays through to the end means more listening time,

732
00:46:58,661 --> 00:47:02,860
more streams, more revenue. The algorithm is optimizing for engagement,

733
00:47:03,229 --> 00:47:07,060
not discovery. And engagement on a per-user basis is

734
00:47:07,092 --> 00:47:10,490
maximized by playing it safe. There's also the editorial layer.

735
00:47:10,842 --> 00:47:14,224
Spotify's editorial playlists— Rap Caviar, Today's Top

736
00:47:14,724 --> 00:47:18,151
Hits, Hot Country, Rock Classics— are curated by Spotify staff.

737
00:47:18,456 --> 00:47:22,214
But those staff are heavily influenced by major label priorities.

738
00:47:22,568 --> 00:47:26,615
Major labels have teams whose entire job is to pitch Spotify

739
00:47:26,808 --> 00:47:30,277
editors for playlist placement. They send gifts, they have

740
00:47:30,777 --> 00:47:34,051
relationships, they have leverage. Independent artists don't

741
00:47:34,551 --> 00:47:38,419
have any of that. So the playlists that drive discovery are dominated

742
00:47:38,467 --> 00:47:42,033
by major label artists. The algorithmic playlists are

743
00:47:42,065 --> 00:47:45,582
tuned for engagement rather than discovery. And the long

744
00:47:45,679 --> 00:47:49,437
tail of independent music, which Spotify claims to champion,

745
00:47:49,854 --> 00:47:53,484
is buried under a pile of major label priorities and

746
00:47:53,984 --> 00:47:57,837
safe recommendations. And then there's Discovery Mode, which we covered earlier.

747
00:47:58,222 --> 00:48:01,675
The payola scheme. Major labels can opt their tracks

748
00:48:02,175 --> 00:48:06,172
into Discovery Mode, accept a lower royalty rate, and get algorithmic

749
00:48:06,253 --> 00:48:09,899
boosts. Independent artists can technically do the same,

750
00:48:09,947 --> 00:48:12,998
but the lower royalty rate, hurts them disproportionately.

751
00:48:13,400 --> 00:48:17,286
The result? The algorithm is even more skewed toward major label

752
00:48:17,479 --> 00:48:20,980
artists, because they're the ones who can afford to pay for placement.

753
00:48:21,269 --> 00:48:25,364
There's another problem. Spotify's algorithm has a feedback loop

754
00:48:25,864 --> 00:48:30,070
problem. If you listen to a track once, even accidentally, even because

755
00:48:30,086 --> 00:48:33,571
you skipped to it, the algorithm treats that as a positive signal.

756
00:48:34,117 --> 00:48:37,361
It then recommends more tracks like that, which you might

757
00:48:37,473 --> 00:48:41,038
listen to, which reinforces the signal, which leads to

758
00:48:41,538 --> 00:48:45,212
more recommendations of the same kind. Your recommendations can drift

759
00:48:45,712 --> 00:48:49,804
in directions you never intended, based on a single accidental listen.

760
00:48:50,318 --> 00:48:53,609
This is why your daily mix sometimes looks like it belongs to a

761
00:48:54,109 --> 00:48:58,009
completely different person. The algorithm got confused by a stray listen

762
00:48:58,201 --> 00:49:02,247
and decided you must be a fan of, I don't know, German techno.

763
00:49:02,536 --> 00:49:05,667
And now you can't get rid of it. And Spotify

764
00:49:06,167 --> 00:49:09,536
doesn't give you good tools to fix this. There's no reset my

765
00:49:09,745 --> 00:49:13,309
recommendations button. There's no I don't like this button on

766
00:49:13,357 --> 00:49:16,954
the home screen the way there is on YouTube. You can block an artist,

767
00:49:17,227 --> 00:49:20,679
but you can't tell the algorithm why you didn't like a particular

768
00:49:21,179 --> 00:49:25,046
track. You're stuck with what it thinks of you. The fundamental issue is

769
00:49:25,094 --> 00:49:29,075
that Spotify's algorithm isn't working for you. It's working

770
00:49:29,268 --> 00:49:32,847
for Spotify. Its job is to maximize your listening

771
00:49:32,879 --> 00:49:36,635
time, which maximizes their revenue, which they then use

772
00:49:37,135 --> 00:49:40,551
to pay artists less per stream while raising your subscription price.

773
00:49:41,305 --> 00:49:44,884
The algorithm is a machine for extracting value from your attention.

774
00:49:45,494 --> 00:49:48,928
It just happens to play music while it does it. You'd think,

775
00:49:49,153 --> 00:49:52,057
given all of this, that Spotify would at least be cheap.

776
00:49:52,699 --> 00:49:56,519
Right? Wrong. They're the most expensive mainstream music service.

777
00:49:57,032 --> 00:50:00,560
And their biggest competitor pays artists twice as much per

778
00:50:01,060 --> 00:50:04,297
stream. Let's talk about Apple Music. Apple Music pays

779
00:50:04,473 --> 00:50:08,258
artists roughly double what Spotify pays per stream. Let me

780
00:50:08,758 --> 00:50:12,523
just say that again. Apple Music pays artists roughly double what

781
00:50:12,571 --> 00:50:16,773
Spotify pays per stream. The widely cited numbers are Spotify,

782
00:50:17,158 --> 00:50:20,589
3/10 of a cent to 5/10 of a cent per stream. Apple Music,

783
00:50:20,766 --> 00:50:24,726
7/10 of a cent to 1 cent per stream. Apple pays twice

784
00:50:24,790 --> 00:50:28,124
as much. And their subscription price is, in most

785
00:50:28,624 --> 00:50:32,693
markets, the same as Spotify's. Or, after Spotify's 2025

786
00:50:32,709 --> 00:50:36,476
and 2026 hikes, cheaper. Why? Because Apple doesn't

787
00:50:36,976 --> 00:50:40,051
need Spotify to make money. Apple makes its money selling iPhones.

788
00:50:40,468 --> 00:50:44,267
Apple Music exists to make the iPhone ecosystem more attractive.

789
00:50:44,491 --> 00:50:47,264
It's a value-add, a loss leader in some quarters.

790
00:50:47,922 --> 00:50:51,577
Apple can afford to pay artists more per stream because Apple

791
00:50:51,689 --> 00:50:55,103
doesn't need Apple Music to be massively profitable on

792
00:50:55,135 --> 00:50:58,421
its own. Own. The profitability comes from the iPhone you bought

793
00:50:58,437 --> 00:51:02,524
to use Apple Music on. Spotify, on the other hand, is just

794
00:51:03,024 --> 00:51:06,322
Spotify. They don't sell phones, they don't sell laptops,

795
00:51:06,611 --> 00:51:10,217
they don't have a hardware business subsidizing their software business.

796
00:51:10,457 --> 00:51:13,983
Every dollar Spotify pays to artists is a dollar

797
00:51:14,483 --> 00:51:18,214
that doesn't go to Spotify's profit margin. So they squeeze. And it's not

798
00:51:18,714 --> 00:51:21,901
just the per-stream payout. Apple Music has shipped feature after

799
00:51:22,401 --> 00:51:26,135
feature that Spotify hasn't. Lossless audio, Spatial audio with

800
00:51:26,167 --> 00:51:30,344
Dolby Atmos. Lyrics that scroll in real time. Live lyrics

801
00:51:30,844 --> 00:51:34,375
that you can sing along to. Apple Music Sing, which lets you mute the vocals

802
00:51:34,440 --> 00:51:38,022
and karaoke any song. All included in the base subscription.

803
00:51:38,279 --> 00:51:42,118
All free. Spotify has, in the same period, raised prices

804
00:51:42,230 --> 00:51:45,427
4 times, added a podcast empire that they then had to

805
00:51:45,443 --> 00:51:48,543
write down, forced an audiobook bundle on users

806
00:51:48,575 --> 00:51:52,415
who didn't want it, and shipped an AI DJ that nobody asked

807
00:51:52,431 --> 00:51:56,190
for. They have not shipped lossless. They have not shipped spatial

808
00:51:56,368 --> 00:52:00,096
audio. They have not shipped Apple Music Sing, but they did add

809
00:52:00,596 --> 00:52:03,482
an AI DJ. So here's the brutal competitive reality.

810
00:52:03,739 --> 00:52:06,799
Spotify is being squeezed from above and below.

811
00:52:07,170 --> 00:52:10,535
From above, Apple Music has the resources of Apple behind it.

812
00:52:11,035 --> 00:52:14,731
Apple can outspend Spotify on licensing, on features, on marketing.

813
00:52:15,070 --> 00:52:18,848
Apple can afford to ship lossless at no extra cost because

814
00:52:19,026 --> 00:52:22,049
Apple can absorb the bandwidth hit. Spotify can't.

815
00:52:22,302 --> 00:52:25,318
From below, YouTube Music is bundled with YouTube Premium,

816
00:52:25,671 --> 00:52:29,490
which means millions of subscribers get YouTube Music essentially

817
00:52:29,586 --> 00:52:33,661
for free as part of a broader subscription. Amazon Music is

818
00:52:33,693 --> 00:52:37,416
bundled with Prime. Spotify is the only major music service

819
00:52:37,448 --> 00:52:41,523
that has to stand on its own. This is why Spotify is raising

820
00:52:41,636 --> 00:52:45,246
prices. They have no other lever. They can't subsidize from a

821
00:52:45,746 --> 00:52:49,064
hardware business. They can't bundle with a broader subscription

822
00:52:49,176 --> 00:52:52,626
that has nothing to do with music. They have to extract

823
00:52:52,643 --> 00:52:56,687
more from their existing subscribers because their existing subscribers

824
00:52:56,783 --> 00:52:59,961
are their only revenue source. And the market is noticing.

825
00:53:00,875 --> 00:53:04,454
Spotify's market share in the US has been slowly eroding.

826
00:53:04,984 --> 00:53:08,723
Not dramatically— they're still the largest music streaming service globally—

827
00:53:09,157 --> 00:53:12,414
but the trend is concerning for them. Apple Music has

828
00:53:12,447 --> 00:53:15,351
grown to around 30% market share in the US.

829
00:53:15,897 --> 00:53:19,312
YouTube Music is gaining. Especially among younger users.

830
00:53:20,050 --> 00:53:24,056
Amazon Music has grown thanks to Prime bundling. Spotify's growth has

831
00:53:24,072 --> 00:53:27,597
slowed, and in some markets, reversed. Spotify's response

832
00:53:28,097 --> 00:53:31,699
to all of this has been: more price hikes, more pivots, more AI

833
00:53:32,199 --> 00:53:35,369
features. They're trying to convince Wall Street that they have a path to

834
00:53:35,869 --> 00:53:39,262
continued growth, while their actual core product—

835
00:53:39,359 --> 00:53:43,349
the music streaming app that you pay for— is, by every measurable

836
00:53:43,381 --> 00:53:47,582
metric, getting worse. There's a question nobody at Spotify

837
00:53:47,710 --> 00:53:51,574
wants to answer: if your competitors can pay artists more,

838
00:53:51,799 --> 00:53:55,295
ship better features, and charge less or the same, while you raise

839
00:53:55,407 --> 00:53:59,031
prices every year, ship fewer features, and pay artists less,

840
00:53:59,576 --> 00:54:03,088
what exactly is your value proposition? What are you offering that

841
00:54:03,588 --> 00:54:07,818
they don't? The honest answer is playlists. Spotify's playlist

842
00:54:08,318 --> 00:54:12,004
curation, even after all the criticism I just gave it, is still better

843
00:54:12,504 --> 00:54:15,820
than Apple Music's. And Discover Weekly, even watered down,

844
00:54:16,093 --> 00:54:18,546
is still better than anything Apple offers.

845
00:54:18,995 --> 00:54:22,635
Spotify's recommendation engine, despite its flaws, is still

846
00:54:22,747 --> 00:54:26,131
the best in the business for surfacing music that matches your taste.

847
00:54:27,077 --> 00:54:31,567
But is that enough? Is playlist curation worth paying 50% more

848
00:54:32,067 --> 00:54:35,544
than you did 3 years ago? Is it worth knowing that the artists you love

849
00:54:35,576 --> 00:54:39,279
are getting paid half what Apple would pay them? For most

850
00:54:39,779 --> 00:54:43,350
users, the answer is yes. For now. Spotify is sticky.

851
00:54:43,734 --> 00:54:47,100
Your playlists are there. Your friends are there. Your Wrapped is there.

852
00:54:47,420 --> 00:54:50,625
Switching is annoying. But stickiness has limits.

853
00:54:51,346 --> 00:54:54,567
And every price hike tests those limits. Let's talk about

854
00:54:55,067 --> 00:54:58,157
the man running this whole show. Because his story is the most

855
00:54:58,657 --> 00:55:01,987
revealing part of all of this. Daniel Ek, the founder and CEO of

856
00:55:02,003 --> 00:55:05,368
Spotify, is a billionaire. He's worth something

857
00:55:05,400 --> 00:55:08,267
around $5 to $7 billion depending on the day.

858
00:55:08,828 --> 00:55:12,192
He founded Spotify in 2006. He's been the

859
00:55:12,692 --> 00:55:15,765
CEO since the beginning. He is the company, in many ways.

860
00:55:16,021 --> 00:55:19,690
In 2023, Daniel Ek started selling Spotify shares.

861
00:55:20,043 --> 00:55:22,558
A lot of them. Hundreds of millions of dollars worth.

862
00:55:23,071 --> 00:55:25,698
Not in a panic, not all at once, but steadily.

863
00:55:26,147 --> 00:55:30,120
Through prearranged trading plans the kind executives use to cash

864
00:55:30,620 --> 00:55:34,285
out without signaling that they think the stock is about to crash.

865
00:55:34,543 --> 00:55:38,082
Perfectly legal. Perfectly normal. But also,

866
00:55:38,260 --> 00:55:41,380
perfectly telling. What's he doing with the money? He's buying a

867
00:55:41,477 --> 00:55:44,926
weapons company. Specifically, Ek has invested hundreds

868
00:55:45,426 --> 00:55:49,200
of millions of euros into Helsing, a European defense AI startup that

869
00:55:49,248 --> 00:55:52,929
makes AI software for fighter jets, drones, and military

870
00:55:53,429 --> 00:55:56,796
applications. He's not just an investor. He's the chairman of the

871
00:55:56,812 --> 00:56:01,001
board. He personally lobbied the German government on Helsing's behalf.

872
00:56:01,513 --> 00:56:04,563
He has made defense tech his second full-time job.

873
00:56:04,885 --> 00:56:08,224
This is not a side hobby. This is a billionaire who

874
00:56:08,337 --> 00:56:12,094
built his fortune on music streaming, on the labor of millions

875
00:56:12,594 --> 00:56:15,514
of artists who are paid 3 tenths of a cent per stream,

876
00:56:16,108 --> 00:56:19,817
deciding that what he really wants to do with his wealth is build the

877
00:56:20,317 --> 00:56:23,783
next generation of weapons systems, while the music platform that

878
00:56:23,815 --> 00:56:26,769
made him rich is, by every measure, decaying.

879
00:56:27,266 --> 00:56:30,615
Now, to be clear, defense technology is a legitimate

880
00:56:30,711 --> 00:56:34,492
industry. Helsing is a real company doing real work that

881
00:56:34,992 --> 00:56:38,418
European governments consider important, especially in the context

882
00:56:38,918 --> 00:56:42,488
of the war in Ukraine. Daniel Ek is allowed to spend his money however

883
00:56:42,504 --> 00:56:45,853
he wants. This is not a moral judgment on defense tech,

884
00:56:46,253 --> 00:56:49,458
but it is a judgment on priorities. The founder

885
00:56:49,958 --> 00:56:54,040
of the world's largest music streaming platform, a platform that has been criticized

886
00:56:54,540 --> 00:56:58,374
by artists, by lawmakers, by the entire independent music

887
00:56:58,438 --> 00:57:01,826
community for its treatment of musicians, has decided

888
00:57:02,326 --> 00:57:06,563
that his time and money are better spent building AI for fighter jets

889
00:57:06,627 --> 00:57:10,015
than fixing the company he founded. Spotify artists are

890
00:57:10,079 --> 00:57:13,483
paid fractions of a cent. Spotify hasn't shipped a promised

891
00:57:13,612 --> 00:57:16,983
lossless feature in 5 years. Spotify's podcast

892
00:57:16,999 --> 00:57:20,098
empire collapsed. Spotify's algorithm has gotten worse.

893
00:57:20,548 --> 00:57:24,112
Spotify's prices have gone up 4 times in 3 years.

894
00:57:24,385 --> 00:57:27,500
And the CEO's attention is elsewhere. Ek still shows

895
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:31,466
up to earnings calls. He still gives interviews about Spotify's future.

896
00:57:32,012 --> 00:57:35,865
But the energy, the focus, the obsession that built Spotify

897
00:57:36,365 --> 00:57:40,040
in the first place— that's gone. He's checked out. He's the defense guy

898
00:57:40,200 --> 00:57:42,737
now. Spotify is the thing that pays for Helsing.

899
00:57:43,315 --> 00:57:46,751
And the stock market has noticed something different. While Ek sells,

900
00:57:47,088 --> 00:57:50,461
institutional investors have been buying. Spotify's stock

901
00:57:50,961 --> 00:57:54,942
has been on a tear, up over 300% from its 2022 lows.

902
00:57:55,296 --> 00:57:58,524
Wall Street loves Spotify right now. They love

903
00:57:58,588 --> 00:58:02,845
the price hikes. They love the margin expansion. They love the AI

904
00:58:03,345 --> 00:58:06,748
narrative. They love that Ek is squeezing more profit out of every

905
00:58:06,780 --> 00:58:10,298
subscriber. Wall Street doesn't care that artists are paid

906
00:58:10,798 --> 00:58:14,764
less. Wall Street doesn't care that the product is getting worse. Wall Street

907
00:58:14,876 --> 00:58:18,632
cares about one thing: profit growth. And Spotify is

908
00:58:18,744 --> 00:58:22,495
delivering profit growth— by squeezing everyone else. So here's

909
00:58:22,995 --> 00:58:26,550
where we are: the CEO is checked out. The stock is at all-time

910
00:58:26,598 --> 00:58:30,477
highs. The product is decaying. Artists are paid less than

911
00:58:30,525 --> 00:58:33,747
ever. Prices are higher than ever. And Wall Street is

912
00:58:33,811 --> 00:58:37,257
cheering. Let's talk about that stock price. Because it's the

913
00:58:37,273 --> 00:58:41,040
most revealing number of all. In early 2023,

914
00:58:41,361 --> 00:58:44,631
Spotify's stock was trading at around $70 per

915
00:58:45,131 --> 00:58:48,173
share. In early 2026, it's over $400.

916
00:58:48,879 --> 00:58:51,411
That's a nearly sixfold increase in 3 years.

917
00:58:52,021 --> 00:58:55,740
Spotify's market capitalization is now north of $80 billion.

918
00:58:56,557 --> 00:58:59,555
Why? Because Spotify finally turned profitable.

919
00:59:00,100 --> 00:59:03,835
After years of operating at a loss, after years of burning cash to

920
00:59:03,851 --> 00:59:06,368
acquire users, build the podcast empire,

921
00:59:06,816 --> 00:59:10,231
expand into new markets, Spotify started making real

922
00:59:10,279 --> 00:59:13,697
money in 2024. Their operating margin went positive.

923
00:59:14,195 --> 00:59:18,034
Their free cash flow exploded. They reported record profits quarter

924
00:59:18,130 --> 00:59:22,146
after quarter. The stock took off. How did they turn profitable?

925
00:59:22,547 --> 00:59:25,936
Not by growing subscribers. Subscriber growth has slowed.

926
00:59:26,177 --> 00:59:29,550
Not by launching successful new products. The podcast

927
00:59:30,050 --> 00:59:33,710
empire collapsed. Audiobooks are a niche. AI features are fluff.

928
00:59:34,192 --> 00:59:37,693
They turned profitable by raising prices and cutting costs.

929
00:59:37,966 --> 00:59:41,236
The prices, we've covered. 4 hikes in 3 years.

930
00:59:41,653 --> 00:59:45,708
50% more revenue per subscriber. The cost cuts are less visible

931
00:59:45,756 --> 00:59:49,491
but more brutal. Spotify has laid off thousands of employees

932
00:59:49,587 --> 00:59:53,258
since 2023. They shut down entire divisions.

933
00:59:53,515 --> 00:59:57,346
They killed shows. They restructured deals. They squeezed every

934
00:59:57,442 --> 01:00:01,048
dollar out of their existing operations. And here's the

935
01:00:01,548 --> 01:00:04,767
most important cost cut of all: they didn't raise artist royalties.

936
01:00:05,072 --> 01:00:09,206
Per-stream payouts went down. The 1,000-stream demonetization

937
01:00:09,222 --> 01:00:12,731
rule redirected money from small artists to major labels.

938
01:00:13,260 --> 01:00:16,593
Discovery Mode let them pay lower rates to artists

939
01:00:17,093 --> 01:00:20,904
who opted in. Every lever Spotify had to reduce the percentage of revenue

940
01:00:21,096 --> 01:00:23,564
that went to artists, they pulled. The result?

941
01:00:24,060 --> 01:00:28,050
Spotify's gross margin improved from around 26% in

942
01:00:28,131 --> 01:00:31,159
2022 to over 30% in 2025.

943
01:00:31,592 --> 01:00:35,663
That 4 percentage point improvement on a $15 billion revenue

944
01:00:35,679 --> 01:00:38,837
base is $600 million in additional profit,

945
01:00:39,189 --> 01:00:42,347
per year, taken directly out of the royalty pool

946
01:00:42,475 --> 01:00:46,242
that should have gone to artists. So when you read that Spotify's stock

947
01:00:46,338 --> 01:00:49,495
is at an all-time high, that they're more profitable than

948
01:00:49,688 --> 01:00:53,294
ever, that Wall Street loves them— understand

949
01:00:53,794 --> 01:00:57,285
what that means. It means they've figured out how to extract more money from

950
01:00:57,381 --> 01:01:01,692
you and from artists while delivering less. That's what their profitability

951
01:01:01,901 --> 01:01:05,586
is built on. Price hikes. Cost cuts. Lower royalties.

952
01:01:05,811 --> 01:01:08,855
Higher margins. Wall Street is celebrating.

953
01:01:09,240 --> 01:01:12,829
Artists are suffering. Listeners are paying more. The CEO

954
01:01:12,958 --> 01:01:16,355
is selling shares to build weapons. The product is decaying.

955
01:01:16,691 --> 01:01:20,281
This is what a successful tech company looks like in 2026.

956
01:01:20,633 --> 01:01:23,566
And the most maddening part? Spotify knows.

957
01:01:24,239 --> 01:01:27,636
They know the artists are unhappy. They know the listeners are frustrated.

958
01:01:27,924 --> 01:01:31,177
They know the listeners are frustrated. They know the competition

959
01:01:31,225 --> 01:01:34,623
is catching up. They just don't care, because the stock price is

960
01:01:34,639 --> 01:01:38,164
the only metric that matters to them, and the stock price is going up.

961
01:01:38,581 --> 01:01:41,994
But there's one more thing they do that I haven't covered yet. The thing

962
01:01:42,106 --> 01:01:45,134
that makes everyone forgive them every December.

963
01:01:45,551 --> 01:01:48,884
Wrapped. Let's talk about Wrapped. Every December,

964
01:01:49,156 --> 01:01:53,244
Spotify releases Wrapped. Your year in music. Your top

965
01:01:53,744 --> 01:01:57,193
artists, top songs, top genres, total minutes listened.

966
01:01:57,482 --> 01:02:00,725
A slick slideshow with bright colors and shareable graphics.

967
01:02:01,094 --> 01:02:05,027
Instagram fills up with Wrapped screenshots. Twitter fills up with

968
01:02:05,107 --> 01:02:08,943
Wrapped screenshots. TikTok fills up with Wrapped reactions.

969
01:02:09,281 --> 01:02:13,117
Wrapped is brilliant. It's the most successful marketing campaign in

970
01:02:13,230 --> 01:02:16,665
music history. It turns every Spotify user into a free

971
01:02:16,681 --> 01:02:19,843
billboard for Spotify. Every December, without fail.

972
01:02:20,614 --> 01:02:24,195
But here's what Wrapped actually is. It's a distraction.

973
01:02:25,191 --> 01:02:28,772
While you're sharing your top 5 artists, Spotify is raising

974
01:02:28,868 --> 01:02:32,802
your subscription price. While you're bragging about your 100,000

975
01:02:32,818 --> 01:02:36,576
minutes listened, Spotify is cutting per-stream royalties to

976
01:02:36,656 --> 01:02:40,093
artists. While you're celebrating your music taste, Spotify is

977
01:02:40,141 --> 01:02:43,288
shipping AI-generated slop into your playlists.

978
01:02:43,802 --> 01:02:47,447
Wrapped is the dessert they serve you so you don't notice that

979
01:02:47,947 --> 01:02:51,815
the main course got smaller and more expensive. And Wrapped has gotten worse

980
01:02:52,008 --> 01:02:55,718
too. The 2024 Wrapped was widely criticized

981
01:02:56,218 --> 01:02:59,829
for being less detailed, less interesting, less shareable

982
01:02:59,878 --> 01:03:03,314
than previous years. Spotify added AI-generated

983
01:03:03,395 --> 01:03:07,233
podcast commentary about your listening habits, which most users

984
01:03:07,345 --> 01:03:10,477
found annoying. They removed some of the granular stats

985
01:03:10,977 --> 01:03:14,685
that power users loved. They turned a beloved annual tradition into

986
01:03:14,733 --> 01:03:18,200
another vehicle for their AI features. Wrapped is also,

987
01:03:18,505 --> 01:03:21,391
structurally, free user research for Spotify.

988
01:03:22,016 --> 01:03:24,838
Every time you share your Wrapped, you're telling Spotify,

989
01:03:25,463 --> 01:03:28,590
and the world, what kind of music you like, how much you

990
01:03:29,090 --> 01:03:32,983
listen, what genres you gravitate toward, how loyal you are to certain

991
01:03:33,079 --> 01:03:36,783
artists. Spotify uses this data to train their recommendation

992
01:03:36,847 --> 01:03:40,310
algorithms, to sell targeted advertising on the free

993
01:03:40,810 --> 01:03:44,238
tier, to negotiate with major labels for better terms. You're giving

994
01:03:44,302 --> 01:03:47,816
them all of that, for free, every December and

995
01:03:47,912 --> 01:03:51,107
thanking them for the privilege. But here's the thing

996
01:03:51,155 --> 01:03:54,912
about Wrapped. It works. People love it. They look forward

997
01:03:55,412 --> 01:03:59,166
to it. They share it. They defend Spotify because of it. Wrapped is the

998
01:03:59,666 --> 01:04:03,468
single best argument that Spotify still makes something people genuinely

999
01:04:03,564 --> 01:04:07,482
love, which makes it hard to argue that Spotify is a bad

1000
01:04:07,514 --> 01:04:10,949
company. Because if they were, why would you look forward

1001
01:04:11,449 --> 01:04:15,061
to their annual recap so much? The answer is that Spotify isn't a

1002
01:04:15,561 --> 01:04:18,017
bad company. They're a good company that's been slowly,

1003
01:04:18,836 --> 01:04:21,134
deliberately optimizing for the wrong things.

1004
01:04:21,889 --> 01:04:25,922
They optimized for engagement instead of discovery. For margin instead

1005
01:04:26,422 --> 01:04:30,565
of artist welfare. For Wall Street instead of musicians. They didn't

1006
01:04:31,065 --> 01:04:34,871
become evil. They became efficient. And efficiency, when your product is

1007
01:04:35,128 --> 01:04:38,438
art, is corrosive. So what should you do? Let's talk

1008
01:04:38,938 --> 01:04:41,775
about that. So, You've listened to all of this. You've heard the numbers.

1009
01:04:42,513 --> 01:04:46,698
You've heard about the price hikes, the royalty cuts, the AI slop,

1010
01:04:47,019 --> 01:04:50,386
the podcast collapse, the audiobook bundling, the broken

1011
01:04:50,450 --> 01:04:54,379
hi-fi promise, the algorithmic decay, the CEO's exit, the stock

1012
01:04:54,395 --> 01:04:58,388
bubble. And you're wondering, should I cancel Spotify? Maybe. Here's my

1013
01:04:58,468 --> 01:05:02,750
honest take. Spotify is still, in many ways, the best

1014
01:05:03,250 --> 01:05:06,470
music streaming app. The recommendation engine, even watered down,

1015
01:05:06,679 --> 01:05:10,527
is the best in the business. The playlist ecosystem is unmatched.

1016
01:05:10,977 --> 01:05:14,044
The social features— collaborative playlists, Blend,

1017
01:05:14,366 --> 01:05:18,365
Wrapped— are genuinely fun. The catalog is huge. The app

1018
01:05:18,445 --> 01:05:21,641
works well. If you care about music discovery, Spotify is

1019
01:05:21,753 --> 01:05:25,688
still the easiest place to find new music. But every year, the gap

1020
01:05:25,752 --> 01:05:28,145
between Spotify and its competitors narrows.

1021
01:05:28,724 --> 01:05:32,353
Apple Music has lossless. Apple Music has spatial audio.

1022
01:05:32,578 --> 01:05:36,208
Apple Music pays artists twice as much. YouTube Music is bundled

1023
01:05:36,708 --> 01:05:40,842
with YouTube Premium. Tidal pays artists even more than Apple. Even Amazon Music

1024
01:05:40,938 --> 01:05:43,983
has lossless now. If you care about audio quality,

1025
01:05:43,999 --> 01:05:47,493
switch to Apple Music or Tidal. If you care about artist

1026
01:05:47,993 --> 01:05:51,243
compensation, switch to Apple Music or Tidal. If you want lossless,

1027
01:05:51,612 --> 01:05:55,362
switch to literally anyone else. If you're tired of price

1028
01:05:55,862 --> 01:05:59,321
hikes, switch to YouTube Music, which is bundled with YouTube

1029
01:05:59,433 --> 01:06:03,199
Premium and often effectively cheaper. If you want

1030
01:06:03,699 --> 01:06:06,869
the best playlist curation and the best recommendation engine,

1031
01:06:07,287 --> 01:06:11,060
and you're willing to pay for it, stay with Spotify. Just know what

1032
01:06:11,560 --> 01:06:14,448
you're paying for, and who you're paying, and what they're doing with the money.

1033
01:06:14,913 --> 01:06:18,751
Here's what I'd actually recommend. Don't make a moral decision.

1034
01:06:19,168 --> 01:06:22,604
Make a practical one. Try Apple Music for a month.

1035
01:06:23,182 --> 01:06:26,779
Try Tidal. See if you miss Spotify. Most people

1036
01:06:26,891 --> 01:06:30,905
don't miss it as much as they think they will. Your playlists can be transferred

1037
01:06:31,405 --> 01:06:34,965
with tools like Soundeze, and tune my music. Your friends will

1038
01:06:34,997 --> 01:06:38,573
still be on Spotify if you want to make collaborative playlists.

1039
01:06:38,926 --> 01:06:42,470
You can keep Spotify free tier for social stuff and pay

1040
01:06:42,615 --> 01:06:46,095
for Apple Music for actual listening. And— this is the most

1041
01:06:46,143 --> 01:06:49,815
important part— buy music. Buy albums on Bandcamp.

1042
01:06:50,072 --> 01:06:53,889
Buy vinyl. Buy merch. Go to concerts. Buy directly

1043
01:06:53,905 --> 01:06:57,417
from artists whenever you can. Streaming was never going to sustain

1044
01:06:57,465 --> 01:07:01,347
a music ecosystem. It was always going to extract from it. The only

1045
01:07:01,444 --> 01:07:04,636
way to actually support artists is to pay them directly,

1046
01:07:05,070 --> 01:07:08,278
in transactions that aren't mediated by a streaming platform's

1047
01:07:08,343 --> 01:07:11,535
royalty math. Spotify has a serious problem.

1048
01:07:11,968 --> 01:07:15,065
Their product is decaying. Their artists are starving.

1049
01:07:15,402 --> 01:07:18,434
Their CEO has checked out. Their stock is a bubble.

1050
01:07:18,771 --> 01:07:22,124
Their pivots have failed. Their promises have been broken.

1051
01:07:22,397 --> 01:07:26,085
Their competition is catching up. But Spotify's biggest problem

1052
01:07:26,309 --> 01:07:30,060
isn't any of those things. Spotify's biggest problem is

1053
01:07:30,092 --> 01:07:33,217
that they've forgotten what they're for. They were supposed to be the

1054
01:07:33,717 --> 01:07:37,352
platform that gave every artist a fair shot and every listener

1055
01:07:37,384 --> 01:07:40,895
access to every song ever recorded. They were

1056
01:07:41,395 --> 01:07:45,366
supposed to be the future of music. Instead, they've become a cautionary

1057
01:07:45,398 --> 01:07:49,181
tale. A story about what happens when a company that promised

1058
01:07:49,681 --> 01:07:52,899
to democratize an industry decides to squeeze it instead.

1059
01:07:53,494 --> 01:07:56,805
You've paid Spotify more money every year since 2023.

1060
01:07:57,432 --> 01:08:01,129
The artists you love have been paid less per stream every year since

1061
01:08:01,629 --> 01:08:05,824
2023. And Spotify's stock has gone up every year since 2023.

1062
01:08:06,258 --> 01:08:09,987
3 numbers. 3 trajectories. All connected.

1063
01:08:10,518 --> 01:08:13,813
You can decide for yourself what they add up to, but if you ask me,

1064
01:08:14,151 --> 01:08:15,967
they add up to a serious problem.

